                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="472923" author="adilger" created="Thu, 25 Sep 2025 17:53:19 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m of mixed opinion on this.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One alternative would be to make the name of the virtual &lt;tt&gt;.Trash&lt;/tt&gt; directory configurable (e.g. tunable &lt;tt&gt;llite.*.trash_can_name&lt;/tt&gt; parameter), to avoid this potential conflict, but I&apos;m not sure if that is needed yet.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;MacOS is using &quot;&lt;tt&gt;.Trash&lt;/tt&gt;&quot; for this functionality (one directory per user), and in theory if Lustre was exported to a Mac (NFS or SMB) then MacOS might start trying to rename files into the &lt;tt&gt;.Trash&lt;/tt&gt; directory when deleted via Finder.  We could potentially allow that, and treat it the same way as unlink of the file (i.e. set &lt;tt&gt;UNRM&lt;/tt&gt; flag, create &lt;tt&gt;trusted.unrm&lt;/tt&gt; xattr to hold original UID/GID/PROJID and set dtime).&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;It would be more tricky if a whole directory is being &quot;deleted&quot; in this way, but potentially a thread on the MDS could recursively process the whole directory, or we return &lt;tt&gt;&amp;#45;EPERM&lt;/tt&gt; in that case?  Returning &lt;tt&gt;&amp;#45;EXDEV&lt;/tt&gt; would cause &lt;tt&gt;rename()&lt;/tt&gt; to try and create a new target directory tree under &lt;tt&gt;.Trash&lt;/tt&gt; and then move the files individually into there.  Maybe good, maybe bad to allow &lt;tt&gt;mkdir()&lt;/tt&gt; in the &lt;tt&gt;.Trash&lt;/tt&gt; directory?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="472776" author="JIRAUSER18433" created="Wed, 24 Sep 2025 17:50:35 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;What is reserving .Trash? And why can&apos;t it work with Lustre transparently?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
